title: For Sale:  Daisy Red Ryder Carbine No.111 Model 40 (1947-1951) - $150
postcontent:
Go to the link to view high resolution images http://redryderforsale.weebly.com/

This is a Daisy Red Ryder Carbine No. 111 Model 40.  I date this bb gun from 1947 - 1951.  It has a black painted aluminum cocking lever which means it was made after 1946.  The wooden handgrip dates it before 1952. 

 Included in the listing is a Red Ryder lucky coin and Daisy BBs.   

This Red Ryder is in Good - Fair Condition.  There is a decent amount of wear throughout the gun but overall it doesn't appear to have been abused.  The bluing on the barrel is very apparent and pleasing.  I tried my best to capture all the details in the photos below.  There may be a couple nuts missing on the back side but everything is tight and functioning.  At some point, someone added some lock washers to the screws as well.  Another things to mention is the minor crease or dent in the barrel, the hair line crack on the handgrip, and 3 BB dents on the backside of the stock.   

 The gun does shoot very well.  It pretty accurate too.  However, I found that it does seem to shoot a bit to the left.  The cocking lever on this old gun does require some muscle to cock it, unlike the new models.  Overall it's a fun gun to shoot a will make a good addition to your collection.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Walther PPQ M1 9mm
postcontent:
I have a mint condition Walther PPQ M1 9mm for sale or trade.  It's been my safe queen.  It has been stored in a temperature and humidity controlled safe.  Comes with factory case, speed loader, and all factory supplied back-straps.  It comes with the original 2, 15 round factory mags.  As an added bonus, this pistol also comes with 2 extra factory Walther PPQ 15 round mags, as well as 3 factory Walther PPQ 17 round mags.  All magazines come from Walther with their "Anti-Friction" coating.   

If your a lefty, I also have an Armordillo Concealment custom kydex holster that I'll throw in.  Armordillo Concealment is probably Raven Concealment's biggest competitor.  

This is by far and wide the nicest factory striker fired pistol on the market.  The PPQ M1 is very sought after as it's 100% ambidextrous, and has the paddle mag release on both sides.  This aids in quicker magazine changes as you don't have to change your grip angle to drop your mag, simply use your trigger finger to release the magazine.  This pistol was inspected in the same German proofing house as H&K (Heckler and Koch).  Out of all of the striker fired pistols that I have fired, the Walther PPQ comes from the factory with the best trigger out of the box.   

I don't need to sell this, I'm simply testing the waters here.  It never get's shot, so it's taking up space in the safe.  I have other projects that I am interested in.  I would like to get my son a Glock 19 (Gen 4) or myself a Kel-Tec Sub-2000 9mm more than I'd like to keep the PPQ.  

We only have until next Thursday to strike a deal, after that it's all paperwork.....  Buyer or person trading must present a valid WA. State CPL.  I priced this pistol and accessories to move.  I don't believe in gouging people at the expense of our trampled liberties due to I-594.

title: For Sale:  Beretta Model 1935
location: Seatac, Seattle, Renton area, Seattle, Washington
postcontent:
This is a Beretta Model 1935, a single-action semi-automatic blowback pistol that fires the .32 ACP ammunition.  Based on some research I did this was at one time issued to an Royal Air Force Officer, as indicated by the Italian Air Force stamp on the frame near the hammer. This pistol was made in or around 1941 or the 19th Mussolini year.  Taken from Wikipedia; 

Pistols made during the Fascist Era are marked with their year of manufacture in two forms: the conventional Julian date in Arabic numerals and the date in the Fascist Era in Roman numerals. The Fascist calendar commenced on 28 October 1922, so a pistol from 1937 may carry either "XV" or "XVI" as its Fascist year. Pistols taken by the armed forces usually exhibit acceptance marks stamped into the frame on the left just above the grip: "RE" (Regio Esercito) for the army, "RM" (Regia Marina) for the navy, or "RA" (Regia Aeronautica) for the Air Force, always in the form of an Eagle wearing a Royal Crown for the Royal air force. 

This handgun is in immaculate condition for being 73 years old.  I only have one magazine.  

Here is your chance to own a piece of history. Price is $550.00 No Trades.

Thank you for looking.

title: For Sale:  1911 Colt Series 70 45 Electroless E Nickel RARE! 1981 Mfg Date
location: North of Lexington/Central KY, Lexington, Kentucky
postcontent: This is a truly rare and unusual piece indeed. In excellent condition this Series 70 Government Model is finished in the rare and desirable electroless nickel. According to Colt, this finish was only used from 1981 to 1983 and was applied by the Nitex company based out of Texas. This finish is NOT the dull "satin" finish that was commonly used in the seventies/eighties on many 1911 pistols. That particular finish was much equivocated in appearance to that of a flat house paint. The serial number dates this 1911 to the correct era. This finish was applied to other Colts as well, including the Python. Next on the list of rarties about this 1911 are the sights, which I can not confirm are factory. This one will be left to the experts here. Nonetheless, the Millett front and rear sights are a wonderful addition to the gun. Truly a unique and very collectible series 70 1911 that is worthy of any collectors safe. A long out of production beauty with only surface scratches that do not penetrate the finish and light handling marks throughout. No box or paperwork with this one, just to note. I am a lifelong KY resident with a KY DL and CCDW permit holder and one of the two must be provided when we meet for the transaction. Shipping will be $30 from my FFL holder to yours if you are an out of state/area buyer and I will accept USPS Money Orders or bank verifiable cashiers checks as payment methods. Any other form of payment remitted will result in a 10 business day hold on shipment.
